Let $\mathbf{a} = \overrightarrow{A},$ $\mathbf{b} = \overrightarrow{B},$ and $\mathbf{c} = \overrightarrow{C}.$  Then $\overrightarrow{D}$ is of the form
\[\overrightarrow{D} = \mathbf{a} + p \mathbf{b} + q \mathbf{c}\]for some constants $p$ and $q.$  Then $D$ has integer coordinates if and only if $p$ and $q$ are integers.

Since $\overrightarrow{AD},$ $\overrightarrow{BD},$ and $\overrightarrow{CD}$ are perpendicular to $\overrightarrow{A},$ $\overrightarrow{B},$ and $\overrightarrow{C},$ respectively,
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \cdot \overrightarrow{AD} &= 0, \\
\mathbf{b} \cdot \overrightarrow{BD} &= 0, \\
\mathbf{c} \cdot \overrightarrow{CD} &= 0.
\end{align*}Then
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + p \mathbf{b} + q \mathbf{c}) &= 0, \\
\mathbf{b} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + p \mathbf{b} + q \mathbf{c}) &= 0, \\
\mathbf{c} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + p \mathbf{b} + q \mathbf{c}) &= 0.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
p &= -\frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}}{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}, \\
q &= -\frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}}{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c}}.
\end{align*}Then
\begin{align*}
p &= -\frac{(0)(4) + (1)(2) + (2)(1)}{(0)(3) + (1)(1) + (2)(5)} = -\frac{2}{13}, \\
q &= -\frac{(0)(3) + (1)(1) + (2)(5)}{(0)(3) + (1)(1) + (2)(5)} = -1.
\end{align*}Therefore,
\[\overrightarrow{D} = \mathbf{a} - \frac{2}{13} \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{c} = \begin{pmatrix} -\frac{26}{13} \\ \frac{23}{13} \\ -\frac{9}{13} \end{pmatrix}.\]Thus, the coordinates of $D$ are $\boxed{\left( -2, 2, -1 \right)}.$

